Fairfax, a former federal prosecutor, and Vogel, a state senator from Fauquier County, are running for lieutenant governor in next month’s election. The post that offers few formal duties other than breaking ties in the state Senate but invariably serves as a launching post for future gubernatorial runs.

Date: Published 5:40 p.m. ET Feb. 8, 2019 | Updated 12:55 p.m. ET Feb. 9, 2019
Caption:
TripAdvisor has named the top-rated pizzerias in every state, based on their site reviews. The list is based on the reviews and opinions of TripAdvisor diners. It takes into account the ratio and quality of pizza reviews compared to overall ratings, along with quality and quantity of reviews received in the past year (ending September 2018). Featured restaurants have a minimum of 4 out of 5 bubbles, 100 reviews and 10 locations or less as of September 2018. The winner in Alabama is Matas Greek Pizza Grinders in Anniston.

"The pizza puts all others to shame. Always fresh with wonderful toppings and feta cheese,” said one TripAdvisor diner.
The winner in Alaska: Moose's Tooth Pub and Pizzeria in Anchorage.

This is what one TripAdvisor diner had to say about Moose's Tooth Pub and Pizzeria in Anchorage, Alaska: "This was the best pizza. What makes the pizza good is the crust. We went with the thick crust and to be honest a basic cheese showed it off. Wish I could keep a pizza warm on the flight home."
The winner in Arizona: Bill's Pizza in Prescott.

This is what one TripAdvisor diner had to say about Bill's Pizza in Prescott, Arizona: “Excellent service, our waitress was prompt courteous and thoughtful. The pizza was perfect in every way. Ours was the BBQ Chicken and we ate every morsel of it.”

The winner in Arkansas: Deluca's Pizzeria Napoletana in Hot Springs.
"The service was amazing! The pizzas were unique but delectable. The sauce is a secret recipe. The owner came to the table and checked on us himself ... The restaurant was small, cozy, clean and friendly," said one TripAdvisor diner.
The winner in California: Bronx Pizza in San Diego.

This is what one TripAdvisor diner had to say about Bronx Pizza in San Diego: “Fast, friendly and ferociously delicious pizza by the slice or whole pie. Hot, crispy thin New York pizza is served by a team who will make you feel like you're a brother back in the Big Apple. They serve 18 different kinds of pizza.”
The winner in Colorado: Pizza Pedal'r in Winter Park

On April 22, 2016, people still walked the streets in a neighborhood in Pike County, Ohio where the Rhoden family was murdered, despite police having reported that the killer was still at-large.
An aerial view of one of the locations in which Rhoden family members were killed. The crime scene spanned four homes.
Ambulances line the street of one of the locations in which Rhoden family members were killed.

A small memorial at the intersection of Rt. 32 and Union Hill Rd. where some of the eight victims were killed. Ages of the victims were 16-44. Top left, Chris Rhoden, 16, Frankie Rhoden and his fiancee Hannah Gilley, Bottom left, Hanna Rhoden, 19 and her mom, Dana Rhoden.
An older family photo Christopher, Hannah and Frankie Rhoden.
An older family photo of Chris Rhoden Sr. and Dana Rhoden in 2000.
Judy Rhoden holding a flyer with photos of her family.
Another memorial sat near Union Hill Road in honor of the eight Rhoden family members who were murdered in 2016.
Ohio Attorney General Mike DeWine and Pike County Sheriff Charles Reader arrive at a press conference a few days following the murders.

Date: Published 12:13 p.m. ET Feb. 4, 2019 | Updated 12:49 p.m. ET Feb. 8, 2019
Caption: Jungle Jim's Big Cheese Festival took place this weekend with cheese offerings from all over the world paired with fine beers, ciders and wine. "The Cheese Lady," Sarah Kaufman of San Diego, sculpts figures from blocks of cheese. (Photo: David Sorcher/for the Enquirer)
My Furry Valentine pet adoption show (Photo: Joe Simon and Gabriella Richards)
Grammy-winning recording artist Amy Grant (Photo: File)
Events calendar guru Luann Gibbs takes a look at the biggest and best events around town this weekend. Find more events at events.cincinnati.com.

1. Jungle Jim's Big Cheese Festival:
Cheese. Is there anything it can't do? Well, okay, so it can't change a flat tire, but nibbling on some can make you feel a whole lot happier as you wait for roadside assistance. Yes, cheese can turn pretty much any situation into a party and complements nearly every foodstuff imaginable. It's perfect all by itself, too.
If cheese is your BFF, the place to be this weekend is the Oscar Event Center at Jungle Jim's International Market (5440 Dixie Highway, Fairfield), where you'll have the opportunity to sample (aka gorge yourself with) unique international cheeses and charcuterie, and for an additional fee, enjoy cheese with specially-paired beers and wines.
Now for a cheesy joke: What do you call cheese that is sad? Bleu cheese. Saturday is already completely sold out but, you've still got a chance to pay homage to the fromage from noon to 5 p.m. Sunday. General admission tickets are $20 in advance and $25 at the door (if still available). Consider yourself something of a big cheese? Splash out on the VIP experience ($75 advance, $80 door, if available) which gets ya additional cheese and drink options, plus a signature tasting glass to sample all-inclusive whiskeys, beers and wines in a special, reserved area. junglefests.com.

2. Winter Xscape Indoor Beach Party:
It's winter in Cincinnati, where we're dealing with a sub-zero degree polar vortex one day and it's sunny and 60 the next. This bi-polar vortex wrecks havoc on a person's wardrobe. Snow boots or sandals? Ski suits or swimsuits? This weekend, opt for warm weather gear and enjoy an indoor vacation on the shores of Newport's Festival Park (between the Taylor Southgate and Purple People bridges) as the Winter Xscape Indoor Beach Party brings a taste of the tropics to the Queen City.
This free-admission "event in a giant tent" boasts an indoor, real-sand beach, a jumbo "island vision" beach board, sand volleyball, coconut bowling, limbo contests, hula dancing with some of the area's favorite bands, a silent disco, tropical food – including a pig roast – and special beach-style drinks complete with tiny umbrellas. Aw, yeah! Grab your flip-flops and hit up the fun anytime from 5 p.m. to 1 a.m. Friday and 1 p.m. to 1 a.m. Saturday. cincinnatifestivalsandevents.com/winter-xscape.

3. Jackie O's Record Fair:
Once upon a time, record stores ruled the landscape. Then came the digital age, when denizens eschewed vinyl records in favor of shiny compact discs. My mom used to say that if you live long enough, everything old is new again. And so it is with vinyl, which never completely disappeared but is thankfully no longer relegated to a small dark corner of the music-buying world. Record fairs are nothing new to those who've kept the vinyl love alive, and chances are good there may already be a few collectors queuing outside Bogart's right now, waiting for the doors to open on Sunday for the first-ever Jackie O's Record Fair (2621 Vine St., Corryville). More than 30 vendors will be on hand selling new releases, reissues, used and highly sought-after mint originals from every era and genre. The show runs from noon to 5 p.m. and costs $5 unless you are one of those already salivating over the idea of mint originals. If so, fork over $10 and get in an hour early to score the goods. bogarts.com.

4. My Furry Valentine:
Did you know that each year over 7 million dogs and cats enter shelters nationwide, and nearly 3 million end up being euthanized? That's a saddening statistic, but when you choose to adopt a pet instead of buying one from a pet store, breeder or online, you are helping to reduce the number of animals killed in shelters. Now imagine this: Dozens of different rescue and shelter groups from around Greater Cincinnati bringing hundreds of adoptable pets to one convenient location. That's My Furry Valentine in a nutshell. All animals participating are fully vaccinated, spayed/neutered and have health records on site. Every adopted pet also goes home with a swag bag of goodies to help make the transition from shelter to forever home.
My Furry Valentine happens from noon-6 p.m. Saturday and Sunday at Sharonville Convention Center (11355 Chester Road). Early birds can get in at 10 a.m. for $25, otherwise, general admission is $5 (free for ages 5-under). myfurryvalentine.com.

5. Dearborn County Home & Garden Show:
Already dreaming of what you'd like to plant this year? Or maybe you're considering a remodel? Let the professionals over at the Home and Garden Show give you a head start on planning your home improvement, interior design, landscaping, lawn care, remodeling, organizing and deck and patio solutions.
The event happens this weekend over at Lawrenceburg Event Center (91 Walnut St.). Admission is $6 per person, with a half-off discount to those who bring a canned or boxed food item for the Dearborn Clearinghouse when purchasing their ticket. The show runs 5-9 p.m. Friday, 10 a.m.-7 p.m. Saturday and noon-5 p.m. Sunday. dearborncountyhba.org.

Honorable Mention:
Now in its 31st year, the Cincinnati Auto Expo showcases the latest in the automotive world from the area's top domestic and import manufacturers. See exotic, high-end luxury vehicles, customs and some of the most spectacular classic and antique collector vehicles in the region. You can get behind the wheel of some of the hottest new vehicles for a test drive, check out a showcase on the history of the pickup and SUV, and get ready for summer at the expo's own mini-RV campsite. There's plenty for kids to do, too, including a jungle gym and trampoline, face painting, balloon animals and even meeting a few live ones visiting from the Cincinnati Zoo.
The expo runs 5-9 p.m. Wednesday, 11 a.m.-9 p.m. Thursday-Friday, 10 a.m.-9 p.m. Saturday and 10 a.m.-6 p.m. Sunday at Duke Energy Convention Center, 525 Elm St., Downtown. Tickets are $11 at the door and kids age 12-under are free. cincinnatiautoexpo.com.

Caption: Bradley Cooper talks about the death of his father with Oprah Winfrey for her "SuperSoul Conversations." (Photo: Jamie McCarthy, Getty Images)

Who knew back in 1986 the world would witness the beginning of the 'Oprah Effect?' Oprah Winfrey, who could read and write before age three, was tapped to read the news on WVOL radio station by her senior year in high school in Nashville.  Here she hosts 'The Oprah Winfrey Show in its first season, 1986.

Already a newsmaker, Oprah Winfrey poses for USA TODAY in 1986. Her many successful pursuits in media, film, education, philanthropy and consumer and politcal clout helped propel her to become one of the most powerful women in the world. She is also the first African-American female billionaire.

Television talk-show host Oprah Winfrey  relaxes in her studio office following a morning broadcast in Chicago, in this Dec. 18, 1985, file photo. Winfrey came to Chicago in 1984 to WLS-TV's morning talk show, 'A.M. Chicago.'  A month later the show was No. 1 in the market. A year later it was renamed "The Oprah Winfrey Show.'
Oprah also gets a starring role as the fiesty Sofia in the 1985 blockbuster "The Color Purple."
Oprah Winfrey is surrounded in her Harpo Productions office with USA TODAY newspapers in a 1987 file photo.

In ABC's Barbara Walters' 20th anniversary retrospective, she shares her best, worst and most unique moments with some of the world's most intriguing personalities. Walters interviewed Oprah Winfrey on April 11, 1988. Winfrey has often said that Walters was a role model for her as a broadcaster.

Winfrey has always been open about her weight challenges.  The world has watched her go up in down in her 25 years of broadcast.  In this Nov. 15, 1988, telecast Winfrey shows off her new figure during taping of her show in Chicago after she lost 67 pounds following a liquid diet and exercise.

Oprah Winfrey doesn't shy away from controversial hot topics. She gestures to the crowd at the Southwestern High School in Baltimore on Nov. 29, 1988, for quiet during the taping of her show on school violence.

Winfrey stands next to a Stairmaster exercise machine during her talk show in Chicago on Nov. 15, 1989. Although Winfrey said she’s managed to keep most of her weight off by adhering to an exercise routine, she acknowledged she has regained 17 of the 67 pounds she lost the prior year.

El Paso Catholic Bishop Mark J. Seitz stands along the border fence at Sunland Park, N.M., during an interfaith gathering of clergy, including many who were visiting from other parts of the country. The clergy members spoke, prayed and visited with people gathered on the Juárez side during a prayer vigil Friday.  Hope Border Institute, a faith-based group focused on defending human rights on both sides of the border, hosted three national delegations to the area. One group, Faith in Public Life, brought 15 Catholic priests, said Camilo Perez Bustillo, director Advocacy and Research for Hope Border Institute. Another was comprised of a network that rose due to immigrant family separations at the border and a third group was called Movimiento de Mujeres y Madres Migrantes, a movement of migrant mothers and women based in New York, Bustillo said. The three groups united under an interfaith framework titled, “The Cry of the Borders.” The gathering was to protest the idea of indefinite family detention until individual immigration cases are decided, a plan that was announced Thursday by the Trump administration.
People gathered on both sides of the border shake hands through the border fence at Sunland Park, N.M. during an interfaith prayer vigil Friday.

Forrest Gregg was 32-25 as head coach from 1980-83. He led the Bengals to their AFC Championship in 1981 and an appearance in Super Bowl XVI.
Paul Brown was 55-56-1 as head coach from 1968-75.
Sam Wyche was 61-66 as head coach from 1984-91. He led the team to its second AFC Championship and 1988 and an appearance in Super Bowl XXIII. The Bengals have not been back to the Super Bowl.
Marvin Lewis was 131-122-3 as head coach from 2003-18. Lewis is the winningest coach in Bengals history but was 0-7 in playoff games during his tenure.

Caption: The Super Bowl has always captured America’s attention. Since its inception in 1967, between 30% to 50% of all Americans have watched the big game each year. With such a large viewership, it’s not just the NFL’s biggest day -- it is the Super Bowl for advertisers as well.   Major corporations  shell out millions of dollars  for just 30 seconds of air time, guaranteed to be watched by at least 100 million Americans and many millions more across the globe. (Photo: Tom Pennington / Getty Images)
1967: Super Bowl I. Cost of a 30-second spot:  $40,000. (Photo: Jimberg13 / Wikimedia Commons)
1978: Super Bowl XII. Cost of a 30 second spot: $185,000. (Photo: Stephen Dunn / Getty Images)
1987: Super Bowl XXI. Cost of a 30 second spot: $575,000. (Photo: Steve Dykes / Getty Images)
1993: Super Bowl XXVII. Cost of a 30 second spot: $850,000. (Photo: Stephen Wade / Getty Images)
1995: Super Bowl XXIX. Cost of a 30 second spot:  $1,150,000. (Photo: George Rose / Getty Images)
2000: Super Bowl XXXIV. Cost of a 30 second spot:  $2,100,000. (Photo: Tom Hauck / Getty Images)
2008: Super Bowl XLII. Cost of a 30 second spot:  $2,700,000. (Photo: Donald Miralle / Getty Images)
2017: Super Bowl LI. Cost of a 30 second spot:  $5,050,000. (Photo: Al Bello / Getty Images)

BRADY: Chihuahua-Russell Terrier mix, 17 weeks old. From: Dog Star Rescue, Conn. 2019 Howl of Fame inductee.

Dowell was killed in the line of duty earlier in the week.

Virginia state politics are in a state of upheaval, with Governor Ralph Northam, State Attorney General Mark Herring, both Democrats, and Republican Senate Majority Leader Tommy Norment involved with past uses associations with blackface and Lt. Governor Justin Fairfax, a Democrat, accused of sexual misconduct by two women.
A Senate page hands out documents to lawmakers, including State Senator Mamie Locke, right, during a Senate session at the Virginia State Capitol, February 8, 2019 in Richmond, Va.
Protestors carry a fake coffin, to symbolize what they call the death of the Democratic Party, toward the Virginia State Capitol, Feb. 7, 2019 in Richmond, Virginia.

Protestors rally against Virginia Governor Ralph Northam outside of the governors mansion in downtown Richmond, Va. on Feb. 4, 2019. Demonstrators are calling for the resignation of Virginia Governor Ralph Northam, after a photo of two people, one dressed as a Klu Klux Klan member and a person in blackface were discovered on his personal page of his college yearbook. Northam said that while he had not appeared in the photo, "many actions that we rightfully recognize as abhorrent today were commonplace" and he was not surprised such material made its way to the yearbook.

Geraldine Mabagos, of Richmond, holds a sign during a protest in Richmond calling for Governor Ralph Northam to resign on Monday Feb. 4, 2019. Northam has rebuffed widespread calls for his resignation after a racist photo surfaced Friday in his 1984 medical school yearbook page.

Caption: Hal Blaine holds up his hands after placing them in wet cement with Don Randi and Glen Campbell, representing The Wrecking Crew at an induction ceremony for Hollywood's RockWalk on June 25, 2008. Drummer Blaine, who played on many of the biggest hits in music history, died of natural causes March 11, 2019, at his home in Palm Desert, California. He was 90.
Jed Allan, soap opera star known for his roles in "Days of Our Lives," "Beverly Hills, 90210," and "Santa Barbara," died March 9  in Palm Desert, California. Allan was 84.

Luke Perry, the beloved "Beverly Hills, 90210" breakout for his role as "Dylan McKay," died March 4, days after suffering a massive stroke. The actor, 52, most recently starred in TV's "Riverdale," playing Fred Andrews, dad of comic-book character Archie Andrews.
Keith Flint, the snarly-voiced, pointy-haired frontman of electronic dance band The Prodigy, was found dead March 4 at his home near London, bandmate Liam Howlett confirmed via Instagram. He was 49.

Janice Freeman, the powerhouse singer who wowed Miley Cyrus and Jennifer Hudson with her blind audition on "The Voice," died March 2. The Season 13 star, who inspired fans with her personal story of surviving cervical cancer and coping with lupus, died from pneumonia and a blood clot that traveled to her heart. She was 33.
Credit/Source: Michael Kovac, Getty Images for COTA

Caption: Nathaniel Taylor, the actor best known as Rollo Lawson, the street-smart best friend of the son on the 1970s sitcom “Sanford and Son,” has died. Taylor died Feb. 27 at the Ronald Reagan UCLA Medical Center in Los Angeles after a heart attack, his son Kaedi Taylor told The Associated Press on March 2. The elder Taylor was 80. Taylor’s character, Rollo, was the sidekick to Lamont Sanford, played by actor Demond Wilson, and often drew the skepticism of TV patriarch Fred Sanford, who thought Rollo was a bad influence on Lamont because he’d spent time in jail.

Andre Previn, the pianist, composer and conductor whose broad reach took in the worlds of Hollywood, jazz and classical music, always rejecting suggestions that his bop ‘n’ blues moonlighting lessened his stature, died Feb. 28. He was 89. Previn was a child prodigy whose family fled Nazi Germany. He was nominated for 13 Academy Awards and won four. Besides “My Fair Lady,” his Oscar-winning orchestrations included “Gigi” (1958), “Porgy and Bess” (1959) and “Irma La Douce” (1963). Through his career, Previn continued to dip in and out of the jazz world. “I don’t ever consciously change gears when I play jazz or classical,” he once said. “It’s all music.”

Lisa Sheridan, known for her roles on the television series "Halt and Catch Fire" and "Invasion," died Feb. 25 at age 44, according to reports. Sheridan's career spanned two decades and included acting credits on "Legacy," "Scandal," "Journeyman" and "NCIS."

Singer-songwriter Mark Hollis, frontman of 1980s British new wave band Talk Talk, died Feb. 25 at the age of 64 after a short illness. Talk Talk formed in 1981 and had hits in several countries with songs including "It's My Life" – covered by No Doubt in 2003 – and  "Life's What You Make it." Both songs were powered by a distinctive synth sound and Hollis' emotive vocals.

Caption: If you expect decadent chocolate desserts at every turn while visiting Hershey, Pennsylvania, you won’t be disappointed. Fire & Grain at Hershey Lodge offers a S’mores Jar that includes graham cracker cake, toasted marshmallow cream and chocolate ganache made, of course, with Hershey’s chocolate.

Hershey is all about chocolate, reflected by Hershey-themed banners and street lamps shaped like Hershey’s Kisses. Attractions include the Hershey Story Museum and the 85-year-old Hershey Theatre. Visit ChocolateTown Square during the annual “Choctoberfest” in October for live music, craft beer and lots of chocolate.

Bartender Drew Scott pours a Reese’s Peanut Butter Cup Martini at Fire & Grain inside Hershey Lodge. The cocktail combines Castries Peanut Rum Crème, 360 Double Chocolate Vodka and Marie Brizard Chocolat Royal liqueur. Hershey offers several chocolate-themed cocktails at various bars inside the lodge and The Hotel Hershey.

One of the house specialties at Fire & Grain is flatbread. Shown is the prosciutto and fig flatbread, which is covered with green onion aioli, prosciutto, figs and arugula, and drizzled with balsamic reduction and garlic oil. “I’ve been making this dough for more than 35 years, and we’ve perfected it,” says chef Michael Cappelli.

Hershey Gardens welcomes visitors with 175 varieties of roses near The Hotel Hershey. The 23-acre green space overlooks the town of Hershey and Hersheypark, and also includes a butterfly atrium, children’s garden and the Hoop House educational center.

Hershey’s Chocolate World is one of the top attractions in Hershey. Visitors can take a free tour to see how cocoa beans are transformed into Hershey’s chocolate. They also can make their own candy bar, enjoy a chocolate tasting session, tour the town of Hershey via trolley, solve a gooey whodunit in the 4D Chocolate Mystery attraction and shop at one of the largest candy stores around.

Patrons at Hershey’s Chocolate World enter details of their personal candy bar on computerized kiosks. They’re able to choose the style of bar, select ingredients and design the label. Then, they watch as their bar makes its way through the production process via conveyor belt.
A child visiting the Create Your Own Candy Bar attraction at Hershey’s Chocolate World observes the mechanized process behind every bar of Hershey’s chocolate.
Rich, melted chocolate drips over flat candy bars on the production line at Hershey’s Chocolate World.

Caption: La Casa Pequena, Oaxaca, Mexico ($150 per night): "Raw, unadulterated and entirely at one with nature, we love how two distinct themes can environmentally coexist here," says BoutiqueHomes. "Inspired by Thoreau’s "Call of the Wild," this beach house rental along the Oaxacan coast is a modern homage to simple living that will inspire you to unplug and reconnect with nature. Down a rambling dirt road in what feels like the middle of nowhere, there stands a striking structure that blends a refined, modern design aesthetic with a raw, primitive spirit. Just a short distance from the surfing mecca of Puerto Escondido in coastal Oaxaca, the property inhabits a solitary spot in the jungle scrub opening out to a private and wild shoreline all your own." (Photo: Camila Cossio)
Punta Cana is a top shoulder season destination. (Photo: Cedric Weber, Shutterstock / Cedric Weber)
Calgary, Canada, is the 11th most up-and-coming summer destination this year, according to American Express Travel. (Photo: VisitCalgary.com)
While Mexico’s Caribbean coast has tourism powerhouses like Cancun and Riviera Maya, further south along the coast are less-developed areas with their own unique beauty.
The three main tourism destinations south of Tulum are the small towns of Bacalar and Mahahual, and the larger city of Chetumal, which is near the Belize border.
At first glance Bacalar looks like a beach destination, although it’s actually 16 miles inland on the shores of the Lagoon of Seven Colors, so named because of its range of hues.
Boating excursions on the Lagoon of Seven Colors are a must-do activity for visitors to Bacalar.
Bacalar attractions include the 18th-century Fort of San Felipe, which contains a pirate museum complete with ship models, weapons of the day and an unearthed pirate skeleton.

Directly south of Bacalar is Cenote Azul. Cenotes are naturally formed freshwater pools that are fed by underground rivers. These were magical sites for the Maya. Today, cenotes offer unique swimming, snorkeling and diving experiences.
If travelers are considering an overnight in Bacalar, and are looking for luxury, they should opt for a stay in the Mía Bacalar Luxury Resort & Spa.

"This is exactly the kind of story I craved as a young gay kid growing up in Ohio," he wrote on Instagram. Click forward to see more LGBTQ celebrities.
Ellen DeGeneres is one of the OG LGBTQ celebs in Hollywood, having come out on TV on her own sitcom in 1997 when it was still a serious career risk to do so.
DeGeneres has been married to actress and model Portia de Rossi since 2008.  The Australian-born actress, 45, came out publicly in 2005 after meeting DeGeneres at an awards show.
Actress Tessa Thompson got candid about her sexuality in a an interview with Net-A-Porter published in June 2018, in which she said she is "attracted to men and also to women."
Once part of the Hollywood super couple "Brangelina," Angelina Jolie has described herself as bisexual. The star dated actress Jenny Shimizu in the 1990s after they met on the set of "Foxfire."
"The Big Bang Theory" star Jim Parsons came out as gay in a 2012 New York Times profile. Parsons married his partner of 15 years last May at the Rainbow Room in New York.
Credit/Source: BRYAN BEDDER, Getty Images for Vulture Festival

Caption: Singer Lance Bass of NSYNC fame first came out in a 2006 interview with People Magazine. At a Hollywood Walk of Fame ceremony for the band in 2018, Bass told the crowd, "Growing up in Mississippi and in a Southern Baptist church, in a town where everyone knows your business, I had a secret. I was gay. At the time, I thought I’d never be able to tell anyone."
Credit/Source: MICHAEL KOVAC, Getty Images for Environmental Media Association

Caption: Former Disney star and singer Miley Cyrus has been very open in the past few years about being pansexual and gender-fluid. "I am literally open to every single thing that is consenting and doesn't involve an animal and everyone is of age. Everything that's legal, I'm down with. Yo, I'm down with any adult -- anyone over the age of 18 who is down to love me," Cyrus said in a 2015 interview with ‘Paper.’ "I don't relate to being boy or girl, and I don't have to have my partner relate to boy or girl."

Actress Evan Rachel Wood of "Westworld" fame came out as bisexual in 2012 via Twitter: “I myself am bisexual and have always ‘joked’ about miley giving me gay vibes,” she wrote. “Not a bad thing! Just an observation.”

While he's famous for having played a womanizer on "How I Met Your Mother," Neil Patrick Harris is very much a family man. Married to his partner, David Burtka, since 2014, Harris is the father of twins.

Date: Published 6:28 p.m. ET Jan. 30, 2019 | Updated 5:21 p.m. ET Jan. 31, 2019
Caption: "Empire" is set to return from winter break on March 13. (Photo: Matt Dinerstein/20th Century Fox)

On March 14, "Empire" star Jussie Smollett returned to court to plead not guilty to 16 counts of disorderly conduct and lying to the police about his alleged attack on Jan. 29. The new charges were filed on March 8.

On Feb. 22, Fox announced it was suspending Smollett, one day after the actor was charged with filing a false police report about his alleged Jan. 29 assault. Fox said his character, Jamal Lyon, would be cut out of the final two episodes of Season 5.

"The events of the past few weeks have been incredibly emotional for all of us," said a statement from 20th Century Fox Television attributed to the show's executive producers. "Jussie has been an important member of our 'Empire' family for the past five years and we care about him deeply. While these allegations are very disturbing, we are placing our trust in the legal system as the process plays out. We are also aware of the effects of this process on the cast and crew members who work on our show and to avoid further disruption on set, we have decided to remove the role of Jamal from the final two episodes of the season,” they said, referring to his character, Jamal Lyon, the scion of a recording-industry family.
Smollett is seen in his Feb. 21 booking photo after turning himself into authorities. The evening before, a grand jury indicted him on a felony count of filing a false police report.

Cook County Judge John Fitzgerald Lyke Jr. addresses Smollett in a courtroom sketch from his bond hearing on Feb. 21. Lyke said he was taken aback by the accusations 
even as he told the actor he has the presumption of innocence. “The most vile and despicable part of it, if it’s true, is the noose," said Lyke, who, like Smollett, is black. "That symbol conjures up such evil in this country’s history."

Assistant State's Attorney Risa Lanier briefs reporters after Smollett's bond hearing. Prosecutors say he paid two brothers to stage the assault and stage-managed the whole thing, choosing the location and telling them to put a rope around his neck, pour bleach on him and yell, "This is MAGA country!"

Jussie Smollett leaves Cook County jail after posting bail on Feb. 21. The judge set his bond at $100,000, required the actor to surrender his passport and forbade him from having any contact with the brothers.
Smollett was reportedly expected back on the set of "Empire" hours after leaving the Cook County jail.

In a press conference following his arrest, Chicago Police Superintendent Eddie Johnson said, "First Smollett attempted to gain attention by sending a false letter that relied on racial homophobic and political language. When that didn’t work, Smollett paid $3,500 to stage this attack. The stunt was orchestrated by Smollett because he was dissatisfied with his salary so he concocted a story about being attacked."

Super Bowl I (Packers 35, Chiefs 10): Green Bay Packers wide receiver Max McGee makes a juggling touchdown catch during the first Super Bowl. Packers quarterback Bart Starr was named MVP.
Super Bowl II (Packers 33, Raiders 14): Legendary Green Bay Packers coach Vince Lombardi is carried off the field after his team's second consecutive Super Bowl win.

Super Bowl III (Jets 16, Colts 7): Quarterback Joe Namath of the New York Jets hands off the football to Matt Snell during Super Bowl III on Jan. 12, 1969. Namath came through on his famous "guarantee" of a Jets upset against the heavily favored Colts.
Super Bowl IV (Chiefs 23, Vikings 7): Kansas City quarterback Len Dawson is grabbed by a Minnesota defender after handing the off to running back Mike Garrett.
Super Bowl V (Colts 16, Cowboys 13): Baltimore kicker Jim O'Brien (80) leaps with joy after kicking the winning field goal against the Dallas Cowboys in the final seconds.
Super Bowl VI (Cowboys 24, Dolphins 3): Dallas Cowboys quarterback Roger Staubach (12) tries to escape the grasp of Miami Dolphins defender Jim Riley.

Super Bowl VII (Dolphins 14, Redskins 7): Miami Dolphins' Jim Mandich takes in a Bob Griese pass near the goal line during the second quarter. The 1972 Miami Dolphins remain the NFL's only team with a perfect record (17-0). The 1948 Cleveland Browns of the AAFC also posted a 14-0 record.
Super Bowl VIII (Dolphins 24, Vikings 7): Larry Csonka of the Miami Dolphins runs down the field. Csonka became the first running back to be named Super Bowl MVP.
Super Bowl IX (Steelers 16, Vikings 6):Pittsburgh Steelers defensive tackle "Mean" Joe Greene encourages his teammates.

Caption: Greater Cincinnati Fly Fishing Show. (Photo: The Enquirer/Patrick Reddy)
Cyclones (Photo: Provided)

Events calendar guru Luann Gibbs takes a look at the biggest and best events around town this weekend. Find more events at events.cincinnati.com. Photo: Canadian geese swim in the Ohio River on Wednesday.

1. Cincy Beerfest
If you are a fan of craft beer, the Cincy Beerfest is your Christmas. Held at Duke Energy Convention Center (525 Elm St., Downtown), Beerfest offers you the chance to sample some of the best local, regional and national craft beer of all styles – over 300 beers from more than 150 breweries – all under one roof, plus there'll be plenty of live music to keep the party going.
There are three sessions to choose from: 7:30-11 p.m. Friday, 1-4:30 p.m. Saturday and 7:30-11 p.m. Saturday. Regular admission ($55) and early admission ($65) get you 25 samples in a 5-ounce souvenir acrylic mug, while the Connoisseurs Reception ($95) gives you early admission plus a souvenir snifter glass, access to a special area with premium draft and large-format beers, appetizers and private restrooms. The event raises money for the Big Joe Duskin Music Foundation. cincybeerfest.com.

2. Cincinnati Auto Expo
Yeah, so the auto expo doesn't actually start until Wednesday, but it's worth mentioning now so that you can prepare, because Duke Energy Convention Center will be packed wall-to-wall with exhibits from domestic and import manufacturers as well as a selection of the most exotic, luxurious and fastest vehicles available. The expo showcases the latest cars, trucks, SUVs, crossovers and hybrids on the market and gives attendees the chance to chat with industry specialists and even test drive the ride of your dreams.
The family-friendly event offers a super selection of fun activities in the Safe Travel Family Zone including face painting, balloon animals and the chance to meet area mascots. On Saturday, a knowledgeable educator from Cincinnati Zoo & Botanical Gardens visits with several zoo animal ambassadors. The expo runs Feb. 6-10: 5-9 p.m. Wednesday, 11 a.m.-9 p.m. Thursday-Friday, 10 a.m.-9 p.m. Saturday, and 10 a.m.-6 p.m. Sunday. Tickets are $11 at the door, $9 online and $8 at Kroger. Kids ages 12 and under get in free. cincinnatiautoexpo.com.

3. Cincinnati Cyclones Frozen 5K/10K
Polar vortex, schmortex, add another layer of Gore-Tex and brave the cold along with Twister, Puckchop and thousands of other crazy – um, I mean hardy – souls as they compete in this unique winter 5K/10K race, which takes runners and walkers on a scenic tour from Mehring Way along the Ohio River and through the Cincinnati Transit Center beneath Second Street. Participants receive a sweet, long-sleeved tech shirt, a distinctive finisher's medal, a voucher for any Cyclones regular season home game and, possibly best of all, a nice cup of hot chocolate to warm you after the race. Ahhhh ...
The race begins at 9 a.m. sharp on Saturday morning and costs $35 (5K) and $40 (10K). Walk-up registration is available at U.S. Bank Arena (100 Broadway, Downtown) from noon-6 p.m. Thursday-Friday, and from 7-9 a.m. Saturday. The race benefits the Cincinnati Cyclones Foundation. cycloneshockey.com/5k.

4. Jewish & Israeli Film Fest Opens
This year marks the 30th year of Cincinnati's Jewish & Israeli Film Festival, which features award-winning personal, impactful, human films from around the world. The festival opens at 7 p.m. Saturday with a screening of "An Act of Defiance," a historical drama about 10 political activists, including Nelson Mandela and his inner circle of black and Jewish supporters, who face possible death sentences for conspiracy to commit sabotage after they are arrested by the apartheid South African government in 1963. This opening night selection happens at the National Underground Railroad Freedom Center (50 E. Freedom Way, The Banks) and features a complimentary drink ticket and a post-film reception.
Other venues for the month-long festival include the Mariemont, Esquire and Kenwood theatres, Union Terminal's Reakirt Auditorium, the Mayerson JCC and 20th Century Theater. The festival runs Feb. 2-21. A festival pass for all films in the series runs $170, with most individual selections costing $12 each. Opening night runs $34. mayersonjcc.org.

5. Greater Cincinnati Fly Fishing Show
If the other four events in this week's top 5 sound a bit like too much work, slow it down, relax and head on over to the Oasis Conference Center (902 Loveland-Miamiville Road, Loveland) to amble through the aisles at the Greater Cincinnati Fly Fishing Show. With more than 75 exhibitors, vendors and fly tyers, there's a little something for all fly fishing enthusiasts. What, you don't know the first thing about fly fishing? Me either, but there will be a beginner's fly fishing question and answer session to help get you started. 
In addition, you'll find fly fishing demonstrations, educational speakers and workshops, a casting pond to try out rods, fishing guides and lodge representatives to answer questions, and a special kids area. The show takes place Saturday from 9 a.m.-4 p.m. and admission is $10. Kids age 12 and under get in free, as do scouts in uniform. buckeyeflyfishers.com/expo2019.

Honorable mention: Super Bowl watch parties: 
Super Bowl Watch Party 5 p.m. Sunday, Mecklenburg Gardens, 302 East University Ave., Corryville. $20, $10 ages 10-under. 513-221-5353. 
Super Bowl LIII VIP Viewing Party 6 p.m. Sunday, Hotel Covington, 638 Madison Ave., Covington.

Honorable mention: Trevor Noah:
Trevor Noah 7:30 and 10 p.m. Friday, Procter and Gamble Hall at Aronoff Center, 650 Walnut St., Downtown. $39.50-$95. cincinnatiarts.org.

Caption: Philadelphia Eagles cornerback Ronald Darby (41) celebrates after breaking up a hail mary pass to the New England Patriots in the fourth quarter in Super Bowl LII at U.S. Bank Stadium. (Photo: Kirby Lee, USA TODAY Sports)
Super Bowl I (Packers 35, Chiefs 10): Green Bay Packers wide receiver Max McGee makes a juggling touchdown catch during the first Super Bowl. Packers quarterback Bart Starr was named MVP.
Super Bowl II (Packers 33, Raiders 14): Legendary Green Bay Packers coach Vince Lombardi is carried off the field after his team's second consecutive Super Bowl win.

Super Bowl III (Jets 16, Colts 7): Quarterback Joe Namath of the New York Jets hands off the football to Matt Snell during Super Bowl III on Jan. 12, 1969. Namath came through on his famous "guarantee" of a Jets upset against the heavily favored Colts.
Super Bowl IV (Chiefs 23, Vikings 7): Kansas City quarterback Len Dawson is grabbed by a Minnesota defender after handing the off to running back Mike Garrett.
Super Bowl V (Colts 16, Cowboys 13): Baltimore kicker Jim O'Brien (80) leaps with joy after kicking the winning field goal against the Dallas Cowboys in the final seconds.
Super Bowl VI (Cowboys 24, Dolphins 3): Dallas Cowboys quarterback Roger Staubach (12) tries to escape the grasp of Miami Dolphins defender Jim Riley.

Super Bowl VII (Dolphins 14, Redskins 7): Miami Dolphins' Jim Mandich takes in a Bob Griese pass near the goal line during the second quarter. The 1972 Miami Dolphins remain the NFL's only team with a perfect record (17-0). The 1948 Cleveland Browns of the AAFC also posted a 14-0 record.
Super Bowl VIII (Dolphins 24, Vikings 7): Larry Csonka of the Miami Dolphins runs down the field. Csonka became the first running back to be named Super Bowl MVP.
Super Bowl IX (Steelers 16, Vikings 6):Pittsburgh Steelers defensive tackle "Mean" Joe Greene encourages his teammates.
